00:52:09.120 --> 00:52:10.860
HANNAH SONG: I'll answer that.

00:52:10.860 --> 00:52:13.390
So the status, then, for
North Koreans in China

00:52:13.390 --> 00:52:14.865
is they're illegally there.

00:52:14.865 --> 00:52:16.490
So the Chinese
government, because they

00:52:16.490 --> 00:52:19.460
don't recognize them, refuses
to acknowledge them as refugees.

00:52:19.460 --> 00:52:21.910
But they are technically
under the UN definition

00:52:21.910 --> 00:52:25.550
of refugee surplus, meaning
they qualify as a refugee

00:52:25.550 --> 00:52:27.130
because of the
circumstances they

00:52:27.130 --> 00:52:29.720
would face once they've
left their country.

00:52:29.720 --> 00:52:31.810
Meaning because of the
risk they would be at

00:52:31.810 --> 00:52:33.810
if they were to be repatriated.

00:52:33.810 --> 00:52:36.390
And so they do qualify
under that definition.

00:52:36.390 --> 00:52:38.230
And so the
international community

00:52:38.230 --> 00:52:41.420
recognizes them as refugees
once they've left North Korea.

00:52:41.420 --> 00:52:43.300
The Chinese government does not.

00:52:43.300 --> 00:52:45.030
And so that's one
of the reasons why

00:52:45.030 --> 00:52:47.280
NGOs like ours have to
play this role in-between.

00:52:47.280 --> 00:52:49.488
Because governments are very
limited in terms of what

00:52:49.488 --> 00:52:52.656
they can actually do to help
North Korean refugees in China.

00:52:52.656 --> 00:52:55.125
As are agencies like
the UNHCR, in fact.

00:52:55.125 --> 00:52:56.750
You know, they're
very limited in terms

00:52:56.750 --> 00:52:58.830
of how they can actually
help North Koreans.

00:52:58.830 --> 00:53:00.320
And that's one of the main
reasons why we bring them out

00:53:00.320 --> 00:53:01.580
through to Southeast Asia.

00:53:01.580 --> 00:53:03.580
And in Southeast Asia,
there are countries there

00:53:03.580 --> 00:53:05.038
where they are
recognized, or where

00:53:05.038 --> 00:53:06.720
they do have an
opportunity, then,

00:53:06.720 --> 00:53:09.370
to apply for refugee
status or for resettlement

00:53:09.370 --> 00:53:11.890
in countries like South
Korea and the United States.

00:53:11.890 --> 00:53:14.120
South Korea will
essentially, you know,

00:53:14.120 --> 00:53:15.780
see them as South
Korean citizens.

00:53:15.780 --> 00:53:18.360
And so they do receive that
citizenship pretty quickly

00:53:18.360 --> 00:53:19.490
upon resettling.

00:53:19.490 --> 00:53:22.450
Coming to the US, for
example, or other countries,

00:53:22.450 --> 00:53:24.524
they come as refugees
and then have

00:53:24.524 --> 00:53:26.440
to undergo the process
of getting a green card

00:53:26.440 --> 00:53:29.560
and then can apply for
citizenship, as well.

00:53:29.560 --> 00:53:32.360
